subsection.p:
Exercises in  show that s\circ
R_{Z,\theta}\circ s^{-1} the MÃ¶bius
transformation T_{Z,\theta} given by z\to e^{i\theta}z
(see
) and that s\circ
R_{X,\pi/2}\circ s^{-1} is the MÃ¶bius
transformation T_{X,\pi/2} given by z\to \frac{z+i}{iz+1}
(see
). The fact () that rotations
of the form R_{Z,\theta},R_{X,\pi/2}
generate \Rot(S^2)  implies that the MÃ¶bius
transformations T_{Z,\theta} and T_{X,\pi/2} generate \S. Therefore \S
is in fact a subgroup of the MÃ¶bius group.

We can say more about the specific form of elements
	  in \S in terms of the group homomorphism {\mathcal
	    T}\colon GL(2,\C)\to \M that sends the
	  matrix \left[\begin{array}{cc} a\amp b\\ c\amp
	    d\end{array}\right] to the MÃ¶bius
	  transformation z\to \frac{az+b}{cz+d} (see
	  ). Observe that the transformations


	      T_{Z,\theta} \amp= {\mathcal T}\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}
	      e^{i\theta/2} \amp 0\\ 0 \amp
	      e^{-i\theta/2}\end{array}\right]\right)


	      T_{X,\pi/2} \amp= {\mathcal T}\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}
	      \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\amp \frac{i}{\sqrt{2}}\\
	      \frac{i}{\sqrt{2}}\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{array}\right]\right)


	  are images of elements of the group SU(2) (see
	  ). Because T_{Z,\theta},T_{X,\pi/2}
	  generate \S,
	  it follows that every element
	  of \S is the image under {\mathcal T}
	  of an element of SU(2).

Setting e^{i\theta}=\frac{a}{a^\ast}
and z_0=\frac{-b}{a}, we have the following alternative
form for T\in \S.
Tz=e^{i\theta}\frac{z-z_0}{z_0^\ast z+1}
